
# Automatic genre identification: a survey

**Authors:** Taja Kuzman, Nikola Ljubešić
**Journal:** Language Resources and Evaluation (2025)
**DOI:** 10.1007/s10579-023-09695-8

---

## Abstract

[cite_start]Automatic genre identification (AGI) is a text classification task focused on genres, i.e., text categories defined by the author's purpose, common function of the text, and the text's conventional form[cite: 860]. [cite_start]Obtaining genre information has been shown to be beneficial for a wide range of disciplines, including linguistics, corpus linguistics, computational linguistics, natural language processing, information retrieval and information security[cite: 861]. [cite_start]Consequently, in the past 20 years, numerous researchers have collected genre datasets with the aim to develop an efficient genre classifier[cite: 862]. [cite_start]However, their approaches to the definition of genre schemata, data collection and manual annotation vary substantially, resulting in significantly different datasets[cite: 863]. [cite_start]As most AGI experiments are dataset-dependent, a sufficient understanding of the differences between the available genre datasets is of great importance for the researchers venturing into this area[cite: 864]. [cite_start]In this paper, we present a detailed overview of different approaches to each of the steps of the AGI task, from the definition of the genre concept and the genre schema, to the dataset collection and annotation methods, and, finally, to machine learning strategies[cite: 865].

---

## 1. Introduction

[cite_start]Genres are text categories, defined by the author's purpose, common function of the text, and the text's conventional form[cite: 882]. [cite_start]They have been studied already in Antiquity, as the Greek philosophers and orators recognized that the manner in which the information is conveyed plays an important role on the receivers' understanding of the message, as well as the efficiency of communication[cite: 883].

[cite_start]The term is widely used in linguistics, rhetoric, literary theory, discourse studies, media theory, as well as computational linguistics and information retrieval studies[cite: 885]. [cite_start]The importance of providing information on genres included in a text collection was also recognized by the authors of reference corpora, such as the British National Corpus (BNC) and the Corpus of Contemporary American English (COCA)[cite: 886].

[cite_start]Since the advent of the World Wide Web, there has been an increased interest in identifying genres in text collections, as the web allowed querying and collecting unprecedented quantities of texts[cite: 887]. [cite_start]There has been large interest in genre identification in the area of information retrieval, as the information on the genre in a query in information retrieval tools would allow users to find the texts that are relevant for them more efficiently[cite: 888]. [cite_start]Furthermore, collecting texts from the web has allowed a significantly faster and cheaper creation of corpora which are essential for language research and development of advanced language resources and technologies[cite: 889].

[cite_start]To obtain the information on the genre of specific texts in large collections of text, automatic genre identification (AGI), a text classification method which categorizes texts into genres, is the only feasible option due to the high data volume[cite: 891]. [cite_start]AGI is primarily researched in the field of language technology which is concerned with computational processing of human languages[cite: 892].

[cite_start]In addition to the benefits of genre identification for information retrieval and corpus creation and curation, it was shown that annotating documents with genre is also beneficial in many other NLP tasks[cite: 899]. For instance:
* [cite_start]In part-of-speech (PoS) tagging of web corpora, using different granularity of PoS sets depending on the genres improves the tagging accuracy[cite: 900].
* [cite_start]Automatic genre identification improves automatic summarization[cite: 901].
* [cite_start]Genres were revealed to be beneficial for machine translation and zero-shot dependency parsing[cite: 902].
* [cite_start]Genre has also been studied in the area of information security, where it can be used for automated genre-aware assessment of credibility of web documents[cite: 903].

[cite_start]However, although various attempts have been made to provide schemata, genre-annotated datasets and classifiers, there are no reference datasets that can be directly used for building an AGI classifier which could be applied to any collection of web documents[cite: 906].

