## 3. Genre schemata

[cite_start]An "inherent problem of web genre classification is that even humans are not able to consistently specify the genre of a given page"[cite: 945]. [cite_start]Thus, it is crucial for the reliability of a genre-annotated dataset that the genre schema supports the annotators[cite: 947].

**Granularity and Structure:**
Schemata used in previous work vary significantly. [cite_start]They range from seven classes to more than a hundred or almost 300 classes[cite: 949]. [cite_start]They are either hierarchical or not[cite: 950]. [cite_start]Most existing schemata consist of around 10 to 20 categories, while some comprise more than 50 genre classes[cite: 951]. [cite_start]Larger granularity usually increases annotation complexity, resulting in lower inter-annotator agreement[cite: 952].

**Development Approaches:**
* **Top-down:** Based on theoretical principles and expert knowledge. Rehm et al. (2008) [cite_start]proposed this approach to avoid choosing genre sets based solely on perception, deriving schemata from category sets proposed by various research groups[cite: 958, 959].
* **Bottom-up:** Based on surveys of web users. [cite_start]This approach revealed to be problematic as respondents were not consistent or used unspecific terms[cite: 965, 966].

**Classification of Schemata based on Aim:**
1.  [cite_start]**High-coverage schemata:** Aim to cover the entire genre composition of the web (e.g., CORE, FTD, GINCO)[cite: 974, 975].
2.  [cite_start]**Information retrieval schemata:** Created to provide genre identification inside search engines, consisting of categories useful for users (e.g., Genre-KI-04, 7-Web-Genre-Collection)[cite: 976, 977].
3.  [cite_start]**Other schemata:** Limited sets used to analyze specific classes (e.g., academic genres, e-shop genres, poetry)[cite: 978].

**Frequent Labels:**
[cite_start]Analysis of 16 schemata shows that out of 280 genre labels, 177 are unique[cite: 991, 992]. [cite_start]The most frequent categories are FAQ and Instruction (7+ schemata), and News, Legal, Personal Home Page, and Review (6 schemata)[cite: 994].

