#### 4.3.1 High-coverage datasets

**The Hierarchical Genre Collection (HGC):**
Based on the genre set proposed by Dewe et al. (1998)[cite_start], this dataset uses a hierarchical schema of 7 main categories and 32 sub-categories[cite: 1256, 1260].


**CORE (Corpus of Online Registers of English):**
Result of extensive work using a bottom-up approach. [cite_start]The schema consists of 8 higher-level categories and 47 specific subcategories[cite: 1342, 1387]. [cite_start]It is one of the largest datasets (approx. 48,000 texts) but had low inter-annotator agreement[cite: 1393].


**GINCO (Slovene Genre Identification Corpus):**
Consists of 1,002 texts. [cite_start]The schema is based on the subcategory level of CORE but is not hierarchical and has lower granularity (23 categories + Other) to improve agreement[cite: 1397, 1423]. [cite_start]It used expert annotators and multi-labelling (primary, secondary, tertiary labels)[cite: 1425, 1427].


**Functional Text Dimensions (FTD):**
Instead of traditional classes, FTD uses 18 dimensions. [cite_start]Texts are annotated based on their similarity to prototypes (distance in FTD space)[cite: 1430, 1431]. [cite_start]The schema has 12 principal categories and 6 additional categories[cite: 1435].


#### 4.3.2 Information retrieval datasets

**Genre-KI-04:**
[cite_start]Consists of 1,239 HTML files annotated with 8 categories (e.g., Help, Article, Discussion, Shop)[cite: 1448, 1449].

**7-Web Genre Collection:**
[cite_start]Consists of 1,400 texts annotated with 7 labels exclusive to the web (e.g., Blog, e-Shop, FAQs)[cite: 1451, 1452].

**20-Genre Collection (MGC):**
[cite_start]Consists of 1,539 texts classified into 20 genres including categories useful for filtering (e.g., Error message)[cite: 1454, 1456].

