### 4.3.3 Other datasets

**Leeds Web Genre Corpus:**
[cite_start]The Leeds Web Genre Corpus is one of the largest English genre datasets, consisting of almost 5,000 texts[cite: 1466]. [cite_start]The dataset consists of two subcorpora, created with the aim of evaluating the proposed method for manual annotation: a balanced, manually collected subcorpus, and a random subcorpus, collected based on automated queries made to a search engine[cite: 1467]. [cite_start]The balanced subcorpus was used to test the reliability of the manual annotation on a more controlled set of texts, and then the annotation campaign was extended to the random subcorpus to test the method in realistic conditions[cite: 1468].

[cite_start]The authors devised their own schema, constructed following the top-down approach, starting from the Genre-KI-04 schema[cite: 1469]. [cite_start]The schema consists of 20 specific genres, including Personal Homepage, Company/Business Homepage, Online Shops, Instruction/How to, Recipe, News Article, Editorial, and others[cite: 1470]. [cite_start]The categories were shown to be able to cover 74% of the texts in the Leeds Corpus, while the remaining were annotated with the category "Other"[cite: 1471].

[cite_start]The dataset was annotated via crowd-sourcing where each text was annotated by 5 participants[cite: 1474]. [cite_start]The annotation campaign was shown to be successful and a high inter-annotator agreement was reported, with the percentage agreement of 88% and Fleiss' kappa of 0.87 on the balanced subcorpus, and the percentage agreement of 78% and Fleiss' kappa of 0.71 on the random subcorpus[cite: 1475].

